n Berlin Book Stores -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCulture and the arts played a central role in the ideology and propaganda of National Socialism from the early years of the movement until the last months of the Third Reich in 1945. Hitler and his followers believed that art and culture were expressions of race, and that “Aryans” alone were capable of creating true art and preserving true German culture. This volume’s essays explore these and other aspects of the arts and cultural life under National Socialism, and are authored by some of the most respected authorities in the field: Alan Steinweis, Michael Kater, Eric Rentschler, Pamela Potter, Frank Trommler, and Jonathan Petropoulos. The result is a volume that offers students and interested readers a brief but focused introduction to this important aspect of the history of Nazi Germany.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aArts, Germany20th centuryvCongresses. 0aNational socialism and artzGermanyvCongresses. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh1 aGoebbels, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuener, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuener, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKater, Michael H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicosia, Francis R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNicosia, Francis R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPetropoulos, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPotter, Pamela M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRents